\begin_layout Section
Research Questions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our research aims to look at a prototype S2P intervention, as well as assess
 the relative importance of two of the key components.
 It will also investigate the role of resources constraints as a potential
 enabling factor and look into peer learning.
 In particular, we will answer the following research questions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Does the provision of site-specific soil nutrient information derived from
 a soil test and the recommendation of a specific fertilizer blend based
 on this information change outcomes of interest? The motivation for this
 research question can be found in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Space
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 component of S2P.
 It tests if providing objectively measured scientific information provided
 in a fairly top-down fashion suffices to instigate behavior change.
 This research question also touches on the discussion whether information
 that allows farmers to optimize yields is useful to them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Does providing advice based on farmer characteristics (farmer practices,
 budget constraints,...) and the environment in which farmer operates (availability
 of fertilizer, prices,...) changes outcomes of interest? This research question
 speaks to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Place
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 component of S2P.
 This research question investigates if information useful for assessing
 yield is important for farmers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Does the provision of site-specific nutrient information and farm-specific
 and farmer-tailored agronomic information with respect to soil nutrient
 management change outcomes of interest? This research question focuses
 on potential interactions between the Space and Place components as implied
 in the S2P approach.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Does the provision of site-specific nutrient recommendations and agronomic
 information with respect to soil nutrient management, combined with a subsidy
 to buy these nutrients at a local agro-dealer, change the outcomes of interest?
 This research question looks at the importance of cash/credit constraints
 in the effectiveness of S2P.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Are there important spillover effects? It is well known that, in addition
 to experiential learning on their own fields, farmers also lean from peers
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "foster1995learning,conley2010learning"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The results of a soil test on a particular plot may also provide valuable
 information for farmers with similar plots in the vicinity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "berazneva2023paying"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In a similar fashion, advice based on farmer characteristics and the environmen
t in which farmer operates may be relevant for similar farmers in the same
 village who are likely to face similar issues related to access to fertilizers,
 marketing of final products, etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Treatment Protocols 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To answer the 5 research questions above, we develop 5 different treatments.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Treatment 1 (T1): In a first treatment, a farmer receives a soil report
 (see example in Appendix 1) derived from a soil test on a plot chosen by
 the farmer (See section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Sampling-and-data"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for more information on the soil tests) , with some key characteristics
 of the soil.
 The report indicates the soil
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

s texture, pH level, cation exchange capacity, percentage organic matter,
 total nitrogen, carbon to nitrogen ratio, as well as the parts per million
 of available P, exchangeable K, calcium, magnesium, iron, manganese, boron,
 copper and zinc.
 Beyond the exact measurements each soil property is given a score on a
 4-point Likert scale (very low, low, high, very high), with emojis, color
 coding and bar charts indicating where the soil is deficient and where
 the levels are sound.
 Using a script, a trained enumerator and/or extension worker then discusses
 the soil report with the farmer to derive a recommended nutrient package
 specific to the crop the farmer wants to grow.
 The farmer is then informed where and how to obtain these nutrients (in
 the form of a particular fertilizer blend).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Treatment 2 (T2): using a simple application (fertilizer optimizer), data
 is collected on inorganic fertilizer application that the farmer is planning
 to use in the upcoming season.
 It asks at what prices the farmer can obtain these fertilizers, and what
 the farmer plans to spend in total on fertilizers.
 It also allows one to input soil nutrient management practices that the
 farmer will use and has used in the past.
 This information is then used to come up with tailor-made suggestions on
 how the farmer can optimize fertilizer use.
 The philosophy behind this treatment is on the economics behind decision
 making related to inorganic fertilizer use.
 More information on the fertilizer optimizer app can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "wortmann2017fertilizer"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Treatment 3: (T3): This treatment combines treatments T1 and T2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Treatment 4 (T4): a voucher to buy the recommended nutrients at a local
 agro-dealer.
 The voucher will be of a value equivalent to the government
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

s fertilizer subsidy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Comparison 1 (C1): A pure control with no soil test, no custom recommendations
 on optimal soil fertility management, and no subsidy.
 They will only provided with a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

blanket
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 recommendation of the three most important practices that can be used to
 improve soil health.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Comparison 2 (C2): Similar to C1, but these control households will be selected
 in villages where no other treatments are implemented.
 The idea is the assess potential spillover effect from our treatments on
 controls that are close to treated farmers.
 
\end_layout

